## Example 3: Employee Payroll System

HR system where salaries are confidential. Only controlled operations (raise, bonus) can modify salary. Salary can never drop below minimum wage.

**File: `payroll/employee.go`**
```go
package payroll

import "fmt"

const minWage = 15000.0  // lowercase = private to this package

type Employee struct {
    Name       string
    Department string
    baseSalary float64  // Private
    bonus      float64  // Private
}

func NewEmployee(name, dept string, salary float64) *Employee {
    if salary < minWage {
        salary = minWage
    }
    return &Employee{
        Name:       name,
        Department: dept,
        baseSalary: salary,
    }
}

func (e *Employee) GiveRaise(percentage float64) {
    if percentage > 0 && percentage <= 50 {
        raise := e.baseSalary * (percentage / 100)
        e.baseSalary += raise
        fmt.Printf("%s got a %.0f%% raise! (+$%.2f)\n", e.Name, percentage, raise)
    } else {
        fmt.Println("ERROR: Raise must be between 1% and 50%!")
    }
}

func (e *Employee) GiveBonus(amount float64) {
    if amount > 0 && amount <= e.baseSalary*0.5 {
        e.bonus = amount
        fmt.Printf("%s received a bonus of $%.2f\n", e.Name, amount)
    } else {
        fmt.Println("ERROR: Bonus cannot exceed 50% of base salary!")
    }
}

// Private helper — only this package can call it
func (e *Employee) totalPay() float64 {
    return e.baseSalary + e.bonus
}

func (e *Employee) DisplayPayslip() {
    fmt.Printf("\n--- Payslip for %s ---\n", e.Name)
    fmt.Printf("Department: %s\n", e.Department)
    fmt.Printf("Base Salary: $%.2f\n", e.baseSalary)
    fmt.Printf("Bonus: $%.2f\n", e.bonus)
    fmt.Printf("Total Pay: $%.2f\n", e.totalPay())
}
```

**Key Takeaway:** Salary is never accessed directly. Business rules (min wage, max raise %, max bonus %) are enforced inside the methods. Notice how even `totalPay()` is lowercase — it's a private helper method.

